ACTUARIAL LEARNING OUTLINE

I. Mathematical Foundations

A. Probability Theory

Random variables (discrete and continuous)
  Probability distributions:
  Bernoulli, Binomial
  Poisson
  Normal
  Exponential
Cumulative distribution functions (CDFs) and PDFs
Expected value, variance, higher moments
Conditional probability and independence
Bayes’ Theorem
Law of Large Numbers
Central Limit Theorem

B. Statistics

Descriptive statistics (mean, variance, skewness, kurtosis)
Sampling methods and bias
Estimation:
  Point estimators
  Maximum likelihood estimation (MLE)
Confidence intervals
Hypothesis testing:
  t-tests, chi-square tests
Correlation and covariance

C. Regression and Predictive Modeling

Linear regression
Logistic regression
Model diagnostics and assumptions
Feature selection
Bias-variance tradeoff

D. Generalized Linear Models (Core Actuarial Tool)

GLM framework:
  Link functions
  Distribution families
Poisson regression (frequency modeling)
Gamma regression (severity modeling)
Model interpretation and validation

E. Financial Mathematics

Time value of money
Interest theory:
Simple and compound interest
Present value and future value
Annuities (immediate and due)
Discounting cash flows
Basic portfolio concepts

II. Actuarial Modeling Concepts

A. Frequency–Severity Framework

Claim frequency modeling
Claim severity modeling
Aggregate loss modeling:
  Expected loss = frequency × severity

B. Risk Modeling

Risk classification
Segmentation of policyholders
Loss distribution modeling
Exposure measurement

C. Model Validation

Goodness-of-fit tests
Residual analysis
Overfitting vs underfitting
Out-of-sample validation

III. Insurance Domain Knowledge

A. Core Insurance Concepts

Premium
Deductible
Policy limits
Coverage types
Claims process
Underwriting basics

B. Risk and Pooling

Risk pooling principles
Diversification
Law of Large Numbers in insurance context

C. Key Insurance Metrics

Loss ratio (claims / premium)
Claim frequency
Claim severity
Combined ratio (if applicable)
Exposure units
                
D. Pricing Principles
                
Expected loss pricing
Expense loading
Profit margin
Risk-based pricing
Rate adequacy
                
E. Reserving (Introductory)
Incurred vs reported claims
Loss reserves
Development over time
                
IV. Underwriting Awareness (Supporting Knowledge)
                
A. Risk Selection
                
Accept/reject decisions
Risk appetite
                
B. Risk Factors
                
Demographic, behavioral, geographic variables
Identification of high-risk profiles
                
C. Adverse Selection
                
Information asymmetry
Impact on pricing and portfolio
                
D. Policy Structuring
                
Deductibles, limits, exclusions
Impact on claim behavior and risk
                
V. Data and Technical Skills
                
A. Data Handling
                
Data cleaning and preprocessing
Missing data handling
Outlier detection
                
B. SQL
                
Data extraction
Joins and aggregations
Data transformation
                
C. Programming (Python or R)
                
Data analysis libraries
Statistical modeling
Automation of workflows
                
D. Excel / VBA / Automation
Advanced Excel modeling
Reporting automation
Dashboard creation
                
VI. Practical Application Workflow
                
Data extraction and validation
Exploratory data analysis
Distribution fitting
Model building (frequency and severity)
Model evaluation
Pricing and business interpretation
Automation and reporting
                
Summary Structure
                
Learn probability and statistics fundamentals
Move into regression and GLMs
Understand financial mathematics
Apply models to insurance problems (frequency, severity, pricing)



                
Learn core insurance concepts and metrics
Build technical skills (SQL, Python/R, Excel automation)
Integrate underwriting awareness into modeling decisions
Continuously apply concepts to real data
